# NAME

@PACKAGE_NAME@ — Cross-platform filesystem event monitoring for Tcl

# SYNOPSIS

**package require @PACKAGE_NAME@**

**@PACKAGE_NAME@::watchdir create** *objectName* *dir*\
**@PACKAGE_NAME@::watchdir new** *dir*\
*objectName* **destroy**

Linux also provides the low-level inotify interface:

**package require inotify**

**inotify::queue create** *objectName* *callback*\
**inotify::queue new** *callback*\
*objectName* **add_watch** *path* ?*mask*?\
*objectName* **rm_watch** *path*\
*objectName* **destroy**

# DESCRIPTION

The **@PACKAGE_NAME@** package monitors files and directories for
changes.  It provides a cross-platform **@PACKAGE_NAME@::watchdir** class
that works on Linux, macOS, and Windows, backed by each platform's
native filesystem notification API:

| Platform  | Backend                   |
|-----------|---------------------------|
| Linux     | inotify(7)                |
| macOS     | FSEvents (CoreServices)   |
| Windows   | ReadDirectoryChangesW     |

On Linux, the package is also available as **package require inotify**
for backwards compatibility, and the low-level **inotify::queue** class
is available for direct inotify access.

# @PACKAGE_NAME@::watchdir CLASS

The **@PACKAGE_NAME@::watchdir** class recursively watches a directory tree
for file creation and deletion.  It is designed to be subclassed —
override the **new_file** and **remove_file** methods to respond to
events.

When constructed, it scans the directory tree for existing files
(calling **new_file** for each) and installs watches on every
subdirectory.  New subdirectories created after construction are
automatically watched.

Files larger than *maxsize* bytes (default 1048576, i.e. 1 MiB) are
ignored.  To change the limit, set the *maxsize* variable before
calling **next** in a subclass constructor.

**@PACKAGE_NAME@::watchdir create** *objectName* *dir*

:   Create a watchdir object named *objectName* watching *dir*.

**@PACKAGE_NAME@::watchdir new** *dir*

:   Create a watchdir object with an auto-generated name watching
    *dir*.

*objectName* **destroy**

:   Stop watching and clean up.

## Methods for subclass override

The following methods are called by the watchdir when file events
occur.  The default implementations are no-ops.  Override them in a
subclass to take action.

*objectName* **new_file** *normpath*

:   Called when a file is created or written.  *normpath* is the full
    path after **normalize_path** processing.

*objectName* **remove_file** *normpath*

:   Called when a file is deleted or moved away.  *normpath* is the
    full path after **normalize_path** processing.

*objectName* **normalize_path** *fqpath*

:   Called to transform a fully qualified path before it is passed to
    **new_file** or **remove_file**.  The default implementation
    returns *fqpath* unchanged.  Override to apply project-specific
    path normalization.

# EXAMPLE

```tcl
package require @PACKAGE_NAME@

oo::class create my_watcher {
    superclass @PACKAGE_NAME@::watchdir

    method new_file normpath {
        puts "New file: $normpath"
    }

    method remove_file normpath {
        puts "Removed: $normpath"
    }
}

my_watcher create watcher /path/to/watched/dir
vwait ::forever
```

# LINUX (INOTIFY) BACKEND

On Linux, the low-level **inotify::queue** class is available for
direct access to the inotify API.  This is useful when you need
fine-grained control over which events to watch, or when monitoring
individual files rather than directory trees.

## inotify::queue CLASS

The **inotify::queue** class wraps a raw inotify file descriptor in a
TclOO object that delivers events asynchronously through a callback.

**inotify::queue create** *objectName* *callback*

:   Create a queue object named *objectName*.

**inotify::queue new** *callback*

:   Create a queue object with an auto-generated name.

Both forms return the name of the queue object created.  The
*callback* will be invoked with each event that arrives on the queue,
with the event details appended as a dictionary argument:

> *callback event-details*

The dictionary *event-details* contains the following keys:

| Key        | Description                                             |
|------------|---------------------------------------------------------|
| **path**   | The path of the file/directory that the watch was registered on. |
| **mask**   | A list of the flags that identify what the event is, from the tables below. |
| **cookie** | Related events (such as a rename) share a unique cookie value. |
| **name**   | When the watch is on a directory and an event occurs on one of its children, this field contains the relative name of the child. |

*objectName* **add_watch** *path* ?*mask*?

:   Add *path* to the list of paths watched in this queue, or update
    the flags of an existing watch if this path was already watched.
    If *mask* is not specified, it defaults to **IN_ALL_EVENTS**,
    otherwise it must be a list containing flags from the event and
    add_watch flag tables below.

*objectName* **rm_watch** *path*

:   Remove a path from the list of watched paths.  If *path* is not
    watched then an error is raised.

*objectName* **destroy**

:   Delete the queue.  All watches feeding this queue are removed and
    the underlying channel is closed.

## inotify::queue example

```tcl
package require inotify

proc something_happened {event_details} {
    dict for {k v} $event_details {
        puts [format "  %-10s %s" $k $v]
    }
}
inotify::queue create queue something_happened
queue add_watch /tmp
vwait ::forever
```
... another process does a "touch /tmp/foo" ...

```
Event happened:
  path       /tmp
  mask       IN_CREATE
  cookie     0
  name       foo
Event happened:
  path       /tmp
  mask       IN_OPEN
  cookie     0
  name       foo
Event happened:
  path       /tmp
  mask       IN_ATTRIB
  cookie     0
  name       foo
Event happened:
  path       /tmp
  mask       IN_CLOSE_WRITE
  cookie     0
  name       foo
```

## Watching files vs directories

When a watch is placed on an ordinary file, the events it generates
relate directly to the watched file itself.  If, however, the path
being watched is a directory, then in addition to receiving events
about the directory itself, it also generates events for its direct
children (but not recursively for the whole subtree under the
directory).  In this case the event generated contains a **name** field
which identifies the relative name of the child under the watched
directory that generated the event.

## Masks

Masks select which event types to receive.  The **Scope** column
indicates whether the flag applies to the watched path itself (**s**),
to children of the watched path (**c**), or both.

| Flag                | Scope | Description                                    |
|---------------------|-------|------------------------------------------------|
| **IN_ACCESS**       | s c   | File was accessed (read).                      |
| **IN_ATTRIB**       | s c   | Metadata changed (permissions, timestamps, extended attributes, etc). |
| **IN_CLOSE_WRITE**  | s c   | File opened for writing was closed.            |
| **IN_CLOSE_NOWRITE**| s c   | File not opened for writing was closed.        |
| **IN_CREATE**       |   c   | File/directory created in watched directory.   |
| **IN_DELETE**        |   c   | File/directory deleted from watched directory. |
| **IN_DELETE_SELF**  | s     | Watched file/directory was itself deleted.     |
| **IN_MODIFY**       | s c   | File was modified.                             |
| **IN_MOVE_SELF**    | s     | Watched file/directory was itself moved.       |
| **IN_MOVED_FROM**   |   c   | File moved out of watched directory.           |
| **IN_MOVED_TO**     |   c   | File moved into watched directory.             |
| **IN_OPEN**         | s c   | File was opened.                               |

Convenience flags: **IN_ALL_EVENTS** (all the above), **IN_MOVE**
(**IN_MOVED_FROM** | **IN_MOVED_TO**), **IN_CLOSE** (**IN_CLOSE_WRITE**
| **IN_CLOSE_NOWRITE**).

Additional flags valid only in the *mask* parameter to **add_watch**:

| Flag               | Description                                         |
|--------------------|-----------------------------------------------------|
| **IN_DONT_FOLLOW** | If the watched path is a symbolic link, watch the link itself rather than the path it points to. |
| **IN_MASK_ADD**    | If this path is already watched, add these flags to those already set, otherwise replace what was set before. |
| **IN_ONESHOT**     | Watch this path for one event, then remove it from the watch list. |
| **IN_ONLYDIR**     | Only watch this path if it is a directory.          |

Additional flags that may appear in event masks:

| Flag               | Description                                         |
|--------------------|-----------------------------------------------------|
| **IN_IGNORED**     | The watch was removed, either explicitly with rm_watch, or because the watched path was deleted, or the filesystem was unmounted. |
| **IN_ISDIR**       | The subject of this event is a directory.           |
| **IN_Q_OVERFLOW**  | Event queue overflowed.  See `/proc/sys/fs/inotify/max_queued_events`. |
| **IN_UNMOUNT**     | The filesystem containing the watched path was unmounted. |

## Kernel limits

**/proc/sys/fs/inotify/max_queued_events**

:   Events queued before **IN_Q_OVERFLOW** is generated.

**/proc/sys/fs/inotify/max_user_instances**

:   Maximum queues per user.

**/proc/sys/fs/inotify/max_user_watches**

:   Maximum watches per queue.

# PLATFORM SUPPORT

| Platform | Status | Backend | Notes |
|----------|--------|---------|-------|
| **Linux** | Tested | inotify(7) | Full inotify::queue + @PACKAGE_NAME@::watchdir |
| **macOS** | Untested | FSEvents | @PACKAGE_NAME@::watchdir only |
| **Windows** | Untested | ReadDirectoryChangesW | @PACKAGE_NAME@::watchdir only |

The macOS and Windows backends have been developed and tested on Linux
using shim libraries that emulate each platform's native API using
inotify.  While this exercises the driver code paths end-to-end, it
cannot replicate the exact semantics of the real platform APIs.

**Testers with access to macOS or Windows are needed** to validate the
FSEvents and ReadDirectoryChangesW backends against the real platform
APIs.  Please report any issues at the project's issue tracker.

On all platforms, **@PACKAGE_NAME@::watchdir** provides the same interface.
On macOS and Windows, recursive watching is handled natively by the
kernel; on Linux, the watchdir manages per-directory inotify watches
internally.

# BUILDING

This package requires Tcl 8.6 or 9.0.  The build system is `meson`,
which will find Tcl using its pkg-config file.  Use the
`PKG_CONFIG_PATH` environment variable to point meson to it if Tcl is
installed in a nonstandard location.

## From a Release Tarball

Download and extract [the release](https://github.com/cyanogilvie/@PACKAGE_NAME@/releases), then:

```sh
tar xf @PACKAGE_NAME@-v@PACKAGE_VERSION@.tar.gz
cd @PACKAGE_NAME@-v@PACKAGE_VERSION@
meson setup builddir --buildtype=release
meson compile -C builddir
meson install -C builddir
```

## From the Git Sources

Fetch [the code](https://github.com/cyanogilvie/@PACKAGE_NAME@) and submodules
recursively, then build:

```sh
git clone --recurse-submodules https://github.com/cyanogilvie/@PACKAGE_NAME@
cd @PACKAGE_NAME@
meson setup builddir --buildtype=release
meson compile -C builddir
meson install -C builddir
```

## Testing

Run the test suite after building:

```sh
meson test -C builddir
```

To test a non-native backend on Linux using the inotify shim:

```sh
meson setup builddir_xnu -Ddriver=xnu
meson test -C builddir_xnu

meson setup builddir_nt -Ddriver=nt
meson test -C builddir_nt
```

